data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear failure message: "expected 3, got 0" vs "expected true"
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Checks every element satisfies the condition
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "All users should be active");

    // Dedicated collection assertion
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Should contain an Admin");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Exact count is more precise; better message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(condition)` | Add a message parameter | Tells you *what* failed |
| `Assert.IsTrue(item != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(item)` | Semantically clear |
| `users.Single()` then null check | `Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(...))` | `Single` throws if missing — masks the real assertion |

**Also available — `CollectionAssert`:**

```csharp
CollectionAssert.AllMatch(users, u => u.IsActive);      // MSTest v3.8+
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);          // reference check
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);        // same items, any order
```

For richer collection assertions (e.g., property-based matching), consider **FluentAssertions**:

```csharp
users.Should().HaveCount(3)
     .And.OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)
     .And.ContainSingle(u => u.Role == "Admin");
```

This gives the clearest failure messages of all.
